  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering, including:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering efforts\n- Provides guidelines for countries to combat financial crimes\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Adopted in 2000\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n\n3. The Palermo Convention\n- Provides framework for international cooperation against organized crime\n- Includes provisions for combating money laundering\n\n4. Basel Committee's Anti-Money Laundering Standards\n- Provides guidance for banking supervision and preventing financial crimes\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Mandatory regulations for EU member states\n- Continuously updated to address emerging financial risks\n\nMost countries have domestic laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminal organizations from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
